<b>Pontederiaceae</b> is the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../329/1651329.xml">
botanical name</link> of a family of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../967/18967.xml">
flowering plants</link>. <p>

The <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../401/4067401.xml">
APG II system</link>, of 2003 (unchanged from the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../323/4067323.xml">
APG system</link>, of 1998) places the family in the order <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../409/5409.xml">
Commelinales</link>, in the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../955/4091955.xml">
commelinid</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../682/6682.xml">
clade</link>, in the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../625/55625.xml">
monocots</link>. It is a small family of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../131/1639131.xml">
heterostylous</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../922/151922.xml">
aquatic plant</link>s, occurring in tropical and subtropical waters. <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<scientist wordnetid="110560637" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../410/8145410.xml">
Charles Darwin</link></scientist>
</person>
 was interested in the specialized form of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../131/1639131.xml">
heterostyly</link> found in the family, known as <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../131/1639131.xml">
tristyly</link>. Not all of the species are heterostylous. The family probably contains fewer than three dozen species.  </p>
<p>

It is best known for the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../608/471608.xml">
water hyacinth</link> (<it>Eichhornia crassipes</it>), which is an invasive species in many waterways. The highly modified <it>Hydrothrix gardneri</it> is a submerged aquatic with a two-flowered <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../918/7675918.xml">
pseudanthium</link>.
</p>
